# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: africa-cricket-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The **2005 Afro-Asia Cup** was a cricket competition played for the first time in 2005 and which is intended to run for at least three years.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The idea was to raise money for the Asian Cricket Council and the African Cricket Association, and the whole venture was given a massive boost when the ICC, somewhat controversially, agreed to give the series of one-day matches full ODI status.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The inaugural competition was a series of three one day matches played between an Asian XI and an African XI.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Controversially, the games have been awarded official One Day International status.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The teams were selected by former Test match players rather than by national selectors.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The ICC expected that there would be a strong competitive tender for television rights.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] However, the main television broadcasters, ESPN/Star and Ten Sports, declined to bid.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The rights were eventually bought by Nimbus Sports for the 2005 competition and the next two competitions in the following years.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] There was much controversy over the final squad lists: many of the leading players were either unavailable for selection, withdrew from participating or chose to fulfil commitments with domestic teams.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Africa won the first match by just two runs, while Asia won the second by 18 runs to set up a series decider.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] However, after Africa had been bowled out for 106, the Asian innings was curtailed by rain, and the match eventually declared a no result.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Thus, the series was tied 1–1 and the trophy shared.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The African squad was selected from players from South Africa, Zimbabwe and Kenya.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] As the first match clashed with Zimbabwe's Test match against New Zealand, the Zimbabweans did not play in the first game.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Justin Ontong was available for selection for the first game instead.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Graeme Smith still had two matches of a four-match suspension to serve, and so was unavailable for the first two games.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The Asian side was selected from players from Pakistan, India, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] With the exception of Bangladesh (whose selector had previously only played in the ICC Trophy), each country had one ex-Test cricketer as a selector: Majid Khan (Pakistan), Ravi Shastri (India), Graeme Labrooy (Sri Lanka) and Shafiq Ul-Haque (Bangladesh).
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The competition was considered to be missing a large number of the top players from each continent, for several underlying reasons.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Pakistan made it clear that its players did not have to play if they did not want to, and leading South African bowler Makhaya Ntini announced that he would be playing for English county side Warwickshire and was unavailable for selection for the African side.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Injuries also ravaged the tournament, as four players pulled out a week before the matches were due to start, whilst other big names – including Sachin Tendulkar – were not even available for selection due to injury.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] In front of a crowd of about 1,000 people at Centurion – usually figures more associated with domestic cricket matches – Africa won the first of three ODIs.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The African side included ten South Africans and two Kenyans – and one of the Kenyans was substituted for a South African without getting the chance to bat.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Zaheer Khan made early breakthroughs as Africa collapsed to 57 for 5 – Justin Ontong and Steve Tikolo both dismissed for ducks – but Ashwell Prince and Mark Boucher set Africa back on the right track with an 86-run partnership.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Prince finished on 78 not out as he ran out of partners to bat with, Africa eventually being dismissed for 198.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Asia, however, lost wickets at regular intervals, but a 24-run ninth-wicket partnership between Zaheer Khan and Shoaib Akhtar looked to turn it Asia's way.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Asia needed to eke out five runs for the last wicket, with twenty-two balls to spare, but Ashish Nehra was bowled by a straight delivery from ODI debutant Dale Steyn, and Asia finished two runs short of victory.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Asia XI rebounded at Kingsmead to square the series with one match to play.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Good contributions from the entire top order – the top six hit one six each, Shahid Afridi getting out the next ball but all the others at least passing 30 – saw Asia XI to 267 for 7, with the two Sri Lankans Kumar Sangakkara and Mahela Jayawardene making half-centuries.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Kenyan Thomas Odoyo was statistically the best bowler for the African XI, with three wickets for 45, making him tied best wicket-taker for the African XI so far in the series.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] After Africa XI had been bowled out for a measly 106, rain poured down steadily on Kingsmead, and the umpires eventually declared that play was not possible.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] The rain had already caused the start of the game to be delayed for two hours, before Shoaib Akhtar and Zaheer Khan unleashed their fast bowling on the African side.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] When Tatenda Taibu departed for 10, the score was 51 for 7, and only good hitting and running from Shaun Pollock, who hit 44 not out, carried Africa past 100.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Steve Tikolo, the top-scorer from the last match, was intriguingly dropped.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] Then, Dale Steyn and Shaun Pollock ripped out the two Asian openers Virender Sehwag and Shahid Afridi, and, with the score eight for 2, the weather intervened.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-afro-asia-cup] No further play was possible, and thus the two continents shared the title.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Kofi Annan, secretary general of the UN has sought to strengthen the partnership between the UN and the African Union for Africa to reach the Millennium Development Goals by 2015.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] He declared that "Africa isn't on schedule to reach the Millennium Development Goals.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] But it will be able to reach these goals if the world partnership, promised a long time ago, does come together completely".
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The question of how to represent Africa in the best possible way in the UN Security Council was delayed, following a disagreement among the member countries of the African Union.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] This was referred to a committee composed of 15 countries to assemble in Swaziland from February 2005.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The mandate of the current chairman, Olusegun Obasanjo, president of Nigeria, was prolonged from July 2005 to January 2006.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Next summits will be held in Libya in July 2005 and in Sudan in January 2006.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The summit also touched the situation in Togo and welcomed a delegation, led by Kokou Tozoun, minister of foreign affairs.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] A statement was made, inviting "the international community to encourage the Togo authorities to do its utmost to establish a swift and peaceful return of the peace process in the country".
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Omar Bongo Ondimba, present chairman of the Cemac, yielded his chair to Teodoro Obiang Nguema, president of Equatorial Guinea.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Tandja Mamadou, president of Niger returned to the chair of the UEMOA following the summit of the organisation in Niamey (Niger) on 30 March 2005.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Different heads of state participated in the summit: Abdoulaye Wade (Senegal), Mathieu Kérékou (Benin), Blaise Compaoré (Burkina Faso), Amadou Toumani Touré (Mali), Henrique Rosa (Guinea-Bissau) and Tandja Mamadou (Niger).
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Togo was represented by Koffi Sama, prime minister, and Côte d'Ivoire by Théodore Mel Eg, minister for regional integration and the African Union.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] In a final communiqué, the UEMOA congratulated itself for "the results on price stability in the Union, following a better provisioning of the food markets" and "welcomed the actions intended to preserve the value of the common currency", the CFA franc.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] During a 6-year period, this agreement envisages broad autonomy for the south of Sudan which will have its own government and an autonomous army.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] At the end of this period, a self-determination referendum will be organized.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The income resulting from oil will be shared in equal share between the south and north.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] In addition, the government will have 70% of the positions in the central administration against 30% for the southern rebels.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Lastly, the Sharia (Islamic law) will be into force only in the north of the country, with Muslim majority.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] It will not be applied in the south, having a Christian and animist majority.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] On 10 January, thousands of Sudanese expressed their joy in the streets of Khartoum.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The National Liberation Council of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) ratified unanimously on 24 January the peace agreement in Rumbek.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] On 5 February 2005, president Gnassingbé Eyadéma died after having led Togo for 38 years.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] According to the constitution, the chairman of the National Assembly should have been acting president until new presidential elections, to be held in 60 days.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The army however decided to bring to power a son of the late president, Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] To endorse the decision of the army, the parliament urgently modified the constitution.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The African Union, the ECOWAS, the UN, the European Union condemned what they called a "coup d'etat" and demanded the re-establishment of the constitutional order.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] In spite of a ban on public demonstrations issued by the government, the principal opposition parties demanded free and pluralist elections and appealed each day for peaceful demonstrations, which gathered several hundreds to a few thousand people.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] These were dispersed by the police, using teargas.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] On 25 February Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma renounced from the position of president of the Republic, and announced to be standing as a candidate to the presidential elections, to be held on 24 April 2005.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Abass Bonfoh, vice-president of the National Assembly became acting president.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The campaign was held in a climate of violence.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The opposition denounced the conditions in which they had to prepare, and request a postponement of the election.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Two days before the poll, François Boko, Minister for the Interior of the temporary government, requested the postponement of the scrutiny.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] In a press conference, he denounced "a suicidal electoral process".
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] It is marked by much violence, resulting in dozens of deaths.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] The results were proclaimed on 26 April: Faure Gnassingbé, wins the election with 60.22% of the votes, before Emmanuel Bob Akitani with 38.19% and Harry Olympio with 0.55%.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] After the announcement, there was an outbreak of demonstrations in several cities of the country, denouncing the massive fraud.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Clashes between demonstrators and the police occurred, involving hundreds of victims, died or wounded.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] Thousands of Togolese took refuge in Benin.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] ECOWAS, the European Union and France recognized the victory of Faure Gnassingbé Eyadema and called for the installation of a government of national unity.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] This was rejected by the radical opposition, that requested the cancellation of the elections because of the massive fraud.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2005-in-africa-p01] On 8 June, Edem Kodjo, president of the *Convergence patriotique panafricaine* (CPP, moderate opposition), is appointed Prime Minister.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] was barred from entering due to the age limit.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] In the second round, Boni won the presidency with a majority of 74.29% against Houndbédji.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] won 64.67% of the vote, thus retaining his presidency.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] On November 15, the Independent Electoral Commission (CEI) announced that Kabila had won the vote with 58.05%, while Bemba had received only 41.95% support, and declared Kabila president.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] upheld the election result, stating that Kabila was the winner by "absolute majority".
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] Throughout the year, rioting and violence was rampant in many parts of the country.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] Out of the total 120 seats, coalition parties had won a total of 99 seats, compared to the 17 won by the 6 parties of the opposition.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] The remaining 4 seats were won by independents.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] No major incidents related to the election were reported.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] was voted in for a second term in office with 54.80%, prevailing over 13 other candidates.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] Confusion over preliminary results led opposition candidates to question the validity of the elections, and official complaints were filed to the constitutional court.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] On December 23, the court ruled that Ravalomanana had indeed won the election.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] Furthermore, some candidates were barred from participating for various reasons.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] The elections were considered to be free and transparent by all observers and political parties.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] narrowly voted to uphold the election result, despite many mentions of irregularities.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] However, a multitude of charges were brought against Besigye in the months leading up to the election, sparking claims of fabrication and widespread protests by Besigye supporters.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2006-in-africa] President of Sudan Omar al-Bashir refuses the deployment of 20,000 *Blue Helmets* in a United Nations peacekeeping force in Darfur in accordance with United Nations Security Council Resolution 1706 adopted on September 1.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] The second **Afro-Asia Cup** was played from 6 June until 10 June 2007, hosted by India.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] The three ODI and one Twenty20 matches were broadcast live on ESPN, after Nimbus had pulled out from the deal with Asian Cricket Council.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] The Twenty20 match did not have official status as a Twenty20 international or a regular Twenty20 match.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] Asia XI claimed the first title in the competition's history, following a tied series in 2005, with a 3–0 whitewash of the Africa XI.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] Asian XI captain Mahela Jayawardene was named player of the tournament for his 217 runs, including a half century and a century, in the three ODIs.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] This cup held the Record for the highest overall runs scored in a 3-match series with 1892 runs being scored.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2007-afro-asia-cup] Later it was broken by India vs England in January 2017 with an overall total of 2090 runs.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The **2022 ACA Africa T20 Cup** was a cricket tournament played in Benoni, Gauteng, South Africa.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The finals tournament were originally scheduled to be held in September 2019, but were moved to March 2020, with the original host city being Nairobi, Kenya.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] On 9 March 2020, the tournament was postponed again due to the COVID-19 pandemic, in line with the Kenyan government's 30-day ban on international gatherings.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The tournament was eventually rescheduled for September 2022.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The tournament finals were originally to be contested by the top two teams from each of three regional qualification events, plus South Africa and Zimbabwe as automatic qualifiers.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] It was later decided to make the tournament open only to associate members of the International Cricket Council, and so two additional teams from the qualifiers would be entered into the finals in place of the two full members.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Ghana and Nigeria qualified from the North-Western region in April 2018, with Cameroon later granted an additional place in the finals.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Botswana, Malawi and Mozambique progressed from the Southern region in November 2018.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The Eastern qualifier was due to be played in Nairobi in July 2018, but did not take place; Kenya and Uganda were automatically advanced to the finals.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Shortly before the finals in September 2022, Nigeria were replaced in the tournament by Tanzania.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] All matches played in the tournament finals had full T20I status as the ICC granted T20I status to matches between all of its members from 1 January 2019.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Uganda defeated Tanzania in the final with Riazat Ali Shah (98*) leading a remarkable chase after the team had needed 49 runs from the last three overs.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The North-Western qualifier for the ACA Africa T20 Cup took place in Lagos, Nigeria, in April 2018, starting two days after the conclusion of the North-Western sub-regional qualifier for the 2021 ICC T20 World Cup.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Cameroon took part in the ACA Africa T20 Cup qualifier, having not participated in the T20 World Cup qualifier.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The Southern qualifier for the ACA Africa T20 Cup took place in Gaborone, Botswana, in November 2018, starting two days after the conclusion of the Southern sub-regional qualifier for the 2021 ICC T20 World Cup.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] Eswatini, Lesotho and Namibia all participated in the T20 World Cup qualifier, but did not take part in the ACA Africa T20 Cup qualifier.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The eight qualified teams were split into two groups, with the top two teams from each group advancing to the semi-finals.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The finals were played at Willowmoore Park in Benoni, Gauteng, South Africa.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] All matches played in the tournament finals had T20I status as the ICC granted T20I status to matches between all of its members from 1 January 2019.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The Kenyan squad was missing the injured Eugene Ochieng, as well as the rested Sachin Bhudia, Alex Obanda and Collins Obuya.
[src:africa-cricket-association/2022-aca-africa-t20-cup] The Ugandan squad was also missing several senior players, with Joseph Baguma, Munir Ismail and Pascal Murungi being promoted from the under-19 team.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The **Africa Cricket Association** (**ACA**) is an international body which coordinates the development of Cricket in Africa.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] It is subordinate to the International Cricket Council, the council is the continent's regional administrative body, and currently has 24 member associations.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The role of the ACA includes promoting the development of cricket in Africa and organising some regional tournaments.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] These have included the ACA Africa T20 Cup and the Africa Women's Twenty20 Championship.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The role of the ACA is complementary to the International Cricket Council (ICC), which organises the regional qualifying tournaments for global events.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The ACA has its origins in the Zone VI Cricket Confederation, which was established in 1991 to coordinate international cricket in Southern Africa along the lines of the African Zone VI Athletics Championships.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The inaugural Zone VI tournament was held in Windhoek in September 1991 with Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, and Zambia participating along with the Oxford University Cricket Club as guests.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The confederation soon secured the support of the United Cricket Board of South Africa and expanded outside of Southern Africa, with Uganda joining in 1994 and Kenya joining in 1995.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] In March 1996, a meeting was held in Johannesburg to discuss the formation of an Africa-wide body.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The inaugural annual general meeting of the Africa Cricket Association (ACA) was held in Harare in August 1997.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The last Zone VI tournament was also held in 1997 and replaced by an Africa Cup open to countries from all around the continent.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] Hoosain Ayob was appointed as full-time development director.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] Peter Chingoka of Zimbabwe was elected chairman of the ACA in 1998, replacing South Africa's Krish Mackerdhuj.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] In 2005, the ACA and the Asian Cricket Council (ACC) established Afro-Asian Cricket Cooperation as a vehicle to promote the Afro-Asia Cup, a series of One Day International (ODI) matches between an Africa XI and an Asia XI to raise funds for the development of cricket on both continents.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] The 2005 Afro-Asia Cup was held in South Africa and suffered from low attendance and a lack of interest from the players, although generating significant television revenues.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] A second tournament was held in India in 2007 but the event was not continued, although several proposals for a revival have been made.
[src:africa-cricket-association/africa-cricket-association] In 2023, the ACA announced a 10-year partnership with Mumbai-based firm Corcom Media Ventures for the organisation, promotion, and broadcasting of ACA tournaments, including the ACA Africa T20 Cup and plans for a Women's Africa T20 Cup and an African Premier League.
